data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()` (MSTest v3+). It checks the type **and** returns the cast result, so you avoid the manual cast (which would throw `InvalidCastException` instead of a clean test failure):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- If `result` is the wrong type, you get a clear assertion failure message instead of an unhandled `InvalidCastException`
- The generic overload returns the typed object, so no separate cast needed
- Single expression replaces cast + null check
